Romans 1 Sermon Plan
====================

Based on the two existing sermons (Romans 1.md and Romans 1 (2024).md),
the broader Romans series, Reformed Baptist convictions, and the text itself.


THE PROBLEM WITH THE EXISTING SERMONS
--------------------------------------

Both existing sermons jump straight to 1:18 and never cover 1:1-17.

That means the congregation has never heard a sermon on:
  - Who Paul is and why he's writing (1:1-7)
  - The gospel DEFINED — promised beforehand, concerning the Son,
    descended from David, declared Son of God by the resurrection (1:2-4)
  - Paul's eagerness and obligation to preach (1:8-15)
  - THE THESIS OF THE ENTIRE EPISTLE: "For I am not ashamed of the gospel,
    for it is the power of God for salvation to everyone who believes,
    to the Jew first and also to the Greek. For in it the righteousness
    of God is revealed from faith for faith, as it is written, 'The
    righteous shall live by faith.'" (1:16-17 ESV)

Romans 1:16-17 is the hinge on which all of Romans turns. Everything
before it introduces it. Everything after it unpacks it. Romans 1-3
unpacks the need (wrath). Romans 3:21-5:21 unpacks the provision
(justification). Romans 6-8 unpacks the result (life in the Spirit).
Romans 9-11 unpacks God's faithfulness. Romans 12-16 unpacks the
application.

Without preaching 1:16-17, the series started mid-sentence.


PROPOSED STRUCTURE: TWO SERMONS
---------------------------------

Sermon 1: Romans 1:1-17 — "The Power of God for Salvation"
Sermon 2: Romans 1:18-32 — "Without Excuse"

This follows the text's natural division:
  1:1-17 = The gospel introduced, defined, and declared
  1:18-32 = The wrath of God against those who suppress the truth

If more space is desired, Sermon 1 could be split:
  1a: Romans 1:1-7 — "Set Apart for the Gospel"
  1b: Romans 1:8-17 — "Not Ashamed"

But 1:1-17 reads as one continuous argument (who I am, what the gospel
is, why I'm eager to preach it, and what it accomplishes) and probably
holds together best as a single sermon.


======================================================================
SERMON 1: Romans 1:1-17 — "The Power of God for Salvation"
======================================================================

Series Position:
  This is the opening of the entire Romans journey. In the "midnight to
  morning" framing, this is the moment before midnight — the last thing
  Paul says before the lights go out in 1:18.

  Romans 1:16-17 is the sunrise promised before the darkness begins.
  Everything from 1:18 through 3:20 is midnight. And when 3:21 says
  "But now" — it's the thesis of 1:16-17 being fulfilled.

Text Outline:

I. THE SERVANT AND HIS MISSION (1:1)
   "Paul, a servant of Christ Jesus, called to be an apostle,
    set apart for the gospel of God"

   Three identities:
   - Servant (doulos — bondservant, slave by choice)
   - Called (not self-appointed; God initiated)
   - Set apart (the same word used for the Pharisees, but now set
     apart FOR the gospel rather than from the world)

   Reformed Baptist emphasis: Paul's calling was sovereign.
   He didn't volunteer. He was drafted. This echoes the doctrine
   of effectual calling — God calls, and the called come.

   Carry forward from existing sermons:
   - The 2024 sermon's personal, conversational tone
   - The emphasis that salvation is God's initiative, not ours

II. THE GOSPEL DEFINED (1:2-4)
    "which he promised beforehand through his prophets in the holy
     Scriptures, concerning his Son, who was descended from David
     according to the flesh and was declared to be the Son of God
     in power according to the Spirit of holiness by his
     resurrection from the dead, Jesus Christ our Lord"

    Four things about the gospel:
    1. It was PROMISED BEFOREHAND — not an afterthought, not Plan B
       (This connects directly to the Winslow/Shultz quote from the
       2024 sermon about God nurturing the tree, the soldiers, the
       iron. That material belongs HERE, not in the wrath section.)
    2. It's found IN THE SCRIPTURES — the Old Testament points to Christ
    3. It concerns GOD'S SON — not a program, not a philosophy, a Person
    4. It involves both FLESH and POWER — descended from David (human),
       declared Son of God by resurrection (divine)

    The gospel is not advice. It is an announcement about a Person.
    It is not "here's how to live." It is "here's what God has done."

    Reformed Baptist emphasis: The gospel was planned from eternity.
    Election, atonement, calling — all predetermined. The cross was
    not reactive. It was the plan.

III. THE CALL OF THE SAINTS (1:5-7)
     "through whom we have received grace and apostleship to bring
      about the obedience of faith for the sake of his name among
      all the nations, including you who are called to belong to
      Jesus Christ, to all those in Rome who are loved by God and
      called to be saints"

     Key phrase: "the obedience of faith" — this is the bookend of
     Romans (it appears again in 16:26). Faith is not opposed to
     obedience; true faith produces obedience.

     "Called to belong to Jesus Christ" — not "chose to join."
     "Loved by God and called to be saints" — loved first, called
     second, holy as a result.

     Reformed Baptist emphasis: The saints are those whom God loved
     and called. Sainthood is not earned; it's received.

IV. PAUL'S EAGERNESS (1:8-15)
    "I am eager to preach the gospel to you also who are in Rome."

    Paul's eagerness flows from three things:
    1. Thankfulness for their faith (v8-10)
    2. Desire to strengthen them with a spiritual gift (v11-12)
    3. Obligation — "I am under obligation both to Greeks and to
       barbarians, both to the wise and to the foolish" (v14)

    He is OBLIGATED. The gospel is not optional sharing. It is a
    debt owed to the world. Not because the world deserves it, but
    because God commands it.

    Carry forward from existing sermons:
    - The missions/people group emphasis (both sermons have this DNA)
    - The 2024 sermon's heart for the unreached (Balija of India)
    - A people group segment fits naturally here, connected to Paul's
      obligation to "all the nations" (v5)

V. THE THESIS (1:16-17)
   "For I am not ashamed of the gospel, for it is the power of God
    for salvation to everyone who believes, to the Jew first and
    also to the Greek. For in it the righteousness of God is revealed
    from faith for faith, as it is written, 'The righteous shall
    live by faith.'"

   This is THE statement. Unpack it carefully:

   1. "Not ashamed" — in a culture that mocked crucifixion, Paul
      announces a crucified Savior. Shame was the weapon Rome used
      against the gospel. Paul refuses it.

   2. "The POWER of God" — not the advice of God, not the suggestion
      of God, not the offer of God. POWER. Dunamis. The gospel
      doesn't make salvation possible; it accomplishes salvation.

   3. "For salvation" — complete rescue: from wrath (ch 1-3),
      into righteousness (ch 3-5), through sanctification (ch 6-8),
      by God's faithfulness (ch 9-11), into transformed living (ch 12-16).

   4. "To everyone who believes" — faith is the instrument, not the
      cause. And as Paul will argue later, even faith is a gift (cf.
      Ephesians 2:8-9, Philippians 1:29).

   5. "To the Jew first and also to the Greek" — the gospel goes
      to all nations. This sets up Romans 9-11.

   6. "The righteousness of God is revealed" — not our righteousness.
      GOD'S righteousness. Given to us. Credited to us. This is
      justification — and it's the heartbeat of Romans.

   7. "From faith for faith" — faith is the beginning, the middle,
      and the end of the Christian life. Not faith plus works. Not
      faith then effort. Faith all the way through.

   8. "The righteous shall live by faith" (Habakkuk 2:4) — quoted
      three times in the NT (Romans 1:17, Galatians 3:11, Hebrews
      10:38). Each emphasizes a different word:
      - Romans: "The righteous SHALL LIVE by faith" (life)
      - Galatians: "The RIGHTEOUS shall live BY FAITH" (justification)
      - Hebrews: "The righteous shall LIVE by faith" (perseverance)

   Reformed Baptist emphasis: The gospel is POWER, not possibility.
   God doesn't make salvation available and wait for takers. He
   accomplishes salvation for His people. This is the ground on which
   the entire epistle stands.

Application:
   - Are you ashamed of the gospel? Where? At work? With family?
   - Do you treat the gospel as power or as advice?
   - Is your faith resting on God's righteousness or your own?

Closing:
   1:16-17 is the promise. Starting next week, 1:18 begins the
   indictment that shows WHY we need this power, this righteousness,
   this faith. The lights are about to go out. But now you know
   what's waiting on the other side of the darkness.


======================================================================
SERMON 2: Romans 1:18-32 — "Without Excuse"
======================================================================

Series Position:
  This is midnight. The darkness begins. Paul's case against humanity
  starts here and doesn't relent until 3:20 ("every mouth stopped").

  The connection to Sermon 1 is direct and deliberate. 1:17 says
  "the righteousness of God is revealed." 1:18 says "the wrath of
  God is revealed." Same God. Two revelations. One in the gospel,
  one against ungodliness. The gospel is good news precisely BECAUSE
  the wrath is real.

Text Outline:

I. THE WRATH REVEALED (1:18-20)
   "For the wrath of God is revealed from heaven against all
    ungodliness and unrighteousness of men, who by their
    unrighteousness suppress the truth."

   Key points:
   - God's wrath is not temper. It is settled, holy opposition to sin.
   - It is REVEALED — not hidden, not future only, but active now.
   - It targets those who SUPPRESS the truth — the verb means to
     hold down, to restrain by force. They know and they push it away.

   General revelation (1:19-20):
   "For his invisible attributes, namely, his eternal power and
    divine nature, have been clearly perceived, ever since the
    creation of the world, in the things that have been made.
    So they are without excuse."

   Carry forward from existing sermons:
   The 2024 sermon's fine-tuning material is excellent here, but
   needs to be TIGHTENED significantly. Select 2-3 of the strongest
   examples rather than listing 8-10:
   - Nuclear resonance (carbon → oxygen if off by 1%)
   - Earth's position (fine-tuned for life)
   - The professor's quote: "the more she studies science the more
     she believes there must be an all-powerful God"

   The point is not a science lecture. The point is v20: "without
   excuse." Creation screams Creator. No one will stand before God
   and say "I didn't know."

   Reformed Baptist nuance: General revelation is sufficient to
   CONDEMN but not to SAVE. It leaves men without excuse but does
   not give them saving knowledge of Christ. Special revelation
   (Scripture, the gospel) is necessary for salvation. This is why
   Paul is "eager to preach" (1:15) — because creation alone cannot
   save. The gospel must go out.

II. THE EXCHANGE (1:21-23)
    "For although they knew God, they did not honor him as God or
     give thanks to him, but they became futile in their thinking,
     and their foolish hearts were darkened. Claiming to be wise,
     they became fools, and exchanged the glory of the immortal God
     for images resembling mortal man and birds and animals and
     creeping things."

    The downward spiral begins with ingratitude (v21) and ends in
    idolatry (v23). The progression:
    1. Knew God → didn't honor Him
    2. Didn't give thanks → became futile in thinking
    3. Futile thinking → darkened hearts
    4. Darkened hearts → claimed wisdom (which was foolishness)
    5. Claimed wisdom → exchanged glory for images

    Carry forward from existing sermons:
    The 2024 sermon's Calvin quote: "The human heart is a factory
    for idols." This is verified — from Institutes I.xi.8. Use it.

    The 2024 sermon's observation that modern idols are not wooden
    statues but self-worship ("the idol reflected in a calm stream,
    or in a mirror") — good, carry forward.

    Reformed Baptist emphasis: This is total depravity in real time.
    Man's problem is not ignorance — they KNEW God. The problem is
    rebellion. The will is enslaved. The mind is darkened. Without
    God's intervention, the spiral only goes down.

III. THE THREE-FOLD GIVING OVER (1:24-32)
     This is the most sobering structure in the passage. Three times
     God "gives them up" or "gives them over":

     A. "God gave them up" to impurity (v24-25)
        "Therefore God gave them up in the lusts of their hearts
         to impurity, to the dishonoring of their bodies among
         themselves, because they exchanged the truth about God
         for a lie and worshiped and served the creature rather
         than the Creator, who is blessed forever! Amen."

        The FIRST giving over: God removes restraining grace.
        This is not God pushing them into sin. It is God stepping
        back and letting them have what they demanded.

     B. "God gave them up" to dishonorable passions (v26-27)
        "For this reason God gave them up to dishonorable passions."

        The SECOND giving over: deeper still. The passions themselves
        become disordered. What was natural becomes unnatural.

        Pastoral note: This passage must be preached with both
        truth and compassion. The point is not to single out one
        sin. The point is the PROGRESSION — when God is exchanged
        for an idol, everything downstream is disordered. Sexual
        sin is a symptom of a worship problem.

     C. "God gave them over" to a debased mind (v28-31)
        "And since they did not see fit to acknowledge God, God
         gave them over to a debased mind to do what ought not
         to be done."

        The THIRD giving over: the mind itself is corrupted. And
        then the vice list: "filled with all manner of unrighteousness,
        evil, covetousness, malice... envy, murder, strife, deceit..."

        Carry forward from existing sermons:
        The 2024 sermon's mirror application is powerful here: "When
        you look at yourself in the mirror of scripture — apart from
        Christ — how do you look? Gossiped lately? Boasted? Been
        foolish? Faithless? Heartless?" Use this.

        The 2024 sermon's Matthew 5:21-22 cross-reference (anger =
        murder) — good, carry forward.

     D. The final indictment (v32)
        "Though they know God's righteous decree that those who
         practice such things deserve to die, they not only do them
         but give approval to those who practice them."

        This is the bottom of the spiral. Not just doing evil but
        APPROVING it in others. The conscience is seared. The moral
        compass is inverted. What was shameful becomes celebrated.

        Reformed Baptist emphasis: This is where Paul is headed in
        chapters 2-3 — the universal indictment. Romans 1:18-32
        is not about "those people out there." It is the mirror held
        up to ALL of humanity apart from Christ. Chapter 2 will turn
        the spotlight on the moral and religious person who reads
        chapter 1 and thinks "I'm not like that."

Application:
   - The wrath of God is not a doctrine to avoid. It is why the
     gospel matters. Without 1:18, 1:16 has no urgency.
   - General revelation leaves all without excuse — but it cannot save.
     That is why we preach. That is why we pray. That is why we send.
   - The "giving over" is a warning: when a culture celebrates what
     God condemns, the spiral is not hypothetical. It is active.
   - But the good news: the same God whose wrath is revealed in 1:18
     has a righteousness revealed in 1:17. The midnight of Romans 1
     is not the end of the story. Romans 3:21 is coming: "But now."

Closing:
   Connect back to the thesis of 1:16-17: the gospel is power
   because the problem is THIS bad. You don't need power for a
   scrape. You need power for a catastrophe. Romans 1:18-32 is the
   catastrophe. The gospel is the power.

   End with gospel.


